# Features of React

## 1. Component-Based Architecture

React applications are divided into small reusable pieces called **components**.

Example:

```
App
│
├── Navbar
├── Sidebar
├── Home
├── Footer
```

Each component is independent.

---

## 2. Virtual DOM

### What is DOM?

DOM = Document Object Model

When HTML loads, the browser creates a tree.

Example:

```html
<body>
    <h1>Hello</h1>
    <button>Click</button>
</body>
```

DOM Tree

```
Body
 ├── h1
 └── Button
```

Traditional JavaScript directly changes the Real DOM, which can be slow.

---

### What is Virtual DOM?

React creates a lightweight copy called the **Virtual DOM**.

Process:

```
State Changes

↓

Virtual DOM Updated

↓

Compare with Previous Virtual DOM

↓

Find Difference

↓

Update Only Changed Elements
```

This comparison process is called **Diffing**.

Updating only the changed elements improves performance.

---

## 3. JSX

React uses **JSX (JavaScript XML)**.

Example:

```jsx
const element = <h1>Hello React</h1>;
```

Instead of:

```javascript
document.createElement("h1");
```

JSX looks like HTML but is actually JavaScript.

---

## 4. One-Way Data Binding

Data flows in one direction:

```
Parent Component

↓

Child Component
```

This makes applications predictable and easier to debug.

---

## 5. Reusable Components

Example:

Instead of writing this three times:

```html
<div class="card">
```

React:

```jsx
<Card />
<Card />
<Card />
```

One component can be reused multiple times.

---

## 6. Fast Rendering

Because of the Virtual DOM, React updates only changed parts instead of reloading the whole page.

---

## 7. Declarative Programming

Instead of telling React **how** to update the UI, you tell it **what** the UI should look like.

Example:

```jsx
<h1>Welcome</h1>
```

React handles the DOM updates automatically.

---

