# Topic 2: JSX (JavaScript XML)

## What is JSX?

**JSX (JavaScript XML)** is a **syntax extension of JavaScript** that allows us to write **HTML-like code inside JavaScript**.

React converts JSX into normal JavaScript before the browser executes it.

For example, instead of writing JavaScript DOM code manually, we write HTML-like syntax.

Without JSX:

```javascript
const element = React.createElement(
    "h1",
    null,
    "Hello React"
);
```

With JSX:

```jsx
const element = <h1>Hello React</h1>;
```

Both produce the same result, but JSX is much easier to read and write.

---

# Why do we use JSX?

Imagine you want to create this webpage:

```html
<h1>Welcome</h1>
<p>Learning React</p>
<button>Click Me</button>
```

Without JSX, you would need many `createElement()` calls.

With JSX:

```jsx
function App() {
    return (
        <div>
            <h1>Welcome</h1>
            <p>Learning React</p>
            <button>Click Me</button>
        </div>
    );
}
```

Much simpler!

---

# How JSX Works

When you write:

```jsx
<h1>Hello</h1>
```

React (using Babel) converts it to:

```javascript
React.createElement(
    "h1",
    null,
    "Hello"
);
```

### Compilation Flow

```text
JSX

↓

Babel Compiler

↓

React.createElement()

↓

JavaScript Object

↓

Browser Displays HTML
```

---

# Rules of JSX

## Rule 1: Return Only One Parent Element

 Incorrect

```jsx
function App() {
    return (
        <h1>Hello</h1>
        <p>React</p>
    );
}
```

React throws an error because two elements are returned.

---

 Correct

```jsx
function App() {
    return (
        <div>
            <h1>Hello</h1>
            <p>React</p>
        </div>
    );
}
```

Output:

```text
Hello

React
```

---

## Rule 2: Close Every Tag

HTML sometimes allows:

```html
<input>
```

In JSX, every tag must be closed.

Correct:

```jsx
<input />
```

```jsx
<br />
```

```jsx
<img src="logo.png" />
```

---

## Rule 3: Use className Instead of class

HTML:

```html
<h1 class="title">Hello</h1>
```

JSX:

```jsx
<h1 className="title">Hello</h1>
```

Why?

`class` is a reserved keyword in JavaScript.

---

## Rule 4: Use htmlFor Instead of for

HTML:

```html
<label for="name">
```

JSX:

```jsx
<label htmlFor="name">
```

---

## Rule 5: JavaScript Expressions Use {}

Anything inside `{}` is treated as JavaScript.

Example:

```jsx
const name = "Ritik";

function App() {
    return (
        <h1>Hello {name}</h1>
    );
}
```

Output

```text
Hello Ritik
```

---

# Expressions Inside JSX

Addition

```jsx
function App() {
    return (
        <h1>{10 + 20}</h1>
    );
}
```

Output

```text
30
```

---

Variables

```jsx
const age = 21;

function App() {
    return (
        <h2>Age = {age}</h2>
    );
}
```

Output

```text
Age = 21
```

---

Functions

```jsx
function greet() {
    return "Good Morning";
}

function App() {
    return (
        <h1>{greet()}</h1>
    );
}
```

Output

```text
Good Morning
```

---

Objects

```jsx
const student = {
    name: "Ritik",
    age: 21
};

function App() {
    return (
        <h1>{student.name}</h1>
    );
}
```

Output

```text
Ritik
```

---

# Using CSS in JSX

Inline CSS is written as an object.

```jsx
function App() {
    return (
        <h1 style={{ color: "blue", fontSize: "40px" }}>
            React
        </h1>
    );
}
```

Notice:

```jsx
style={{ }}
```

* First `{}` → JavaScript expression.
* Second `{}` → JavaScript object.

---

# Comments in JSX

Incorrect

```jsx
<!-- Comment -->
```

Correct

```jsx
{/* This is a JSX comment */}
```

Example

```jsx
function App() {
    return (
        <div>
            {/* Heading */}
            <h1>Hello</h1>
        </div>
    );
}
```

---

# JSX Attributes

Example

```jsx
function App() {
    return (
        <img
            src="logo.png"
            alt="Logo"
            width="200"
        />
    );
}
```

Everything looks like HTML but follows JavaScript naming rules.

---

# Fragments

Instead of wrapping everything inside `<div>`, React provides **Fragments**.

Using Fragment:

```jsx
function App() {
    return (
        <>
            <h1>Hello</h1>
            <p>Welcome</p>
        </>
    );
}
```

React doesn't create an extra `<div>` in the DOM.

---

# JSX vs HTML

| HTML                   | JSX                     |
| ---------------------- | ----------------------- |
| class                  | className               |
| for                    | htmlFor                 |
| onclick                | onClick                 |
| inline style as string | inline style as object  |
| Comments `<!-- -->`    | `{/* */}`               |
| Tags may remain open   | All tags must be closed |

---

# Complete Example

```jsx
function App() {

    const name = "Ritik";
    const age = 21;

    return (
        <>
            <h1>Hello {name}</h1>

            <h2>Age : {age}</h2>

            <p>Welcome to React</p>

            <button>Click Me</button>
        </>
    );
}

export default App;
```

Output:

```text
Hello Ritik

Age : 21

Welcome to React

[Click Me]
```

